{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476698"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:50:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:50:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13928"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13928"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.04,0.12,0.06,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96931"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6547"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79546"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"12909"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13441"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13850"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45227"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96931"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with community-acquired pneumonia. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is admitted to the paediatric ward and commenced on intravenous benzylpenicillin. Twelve hours after admission, the nurse pages the duty intern because the patient\u0027s temperature has risen to 38.5\u00b0C. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, and oxygen saturation 98% on room air. His parent reports that the boy feels \u0027a bit warm\u0027 but he is otherwise comfortable, playing with toys, and in no distress.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer paracetamol","Administer ibuprofen","Change antibiotic to ceftriaxone","Increase intravenous fluid rate","Reassure and monitor"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassure and monitor\u003C/strong\u003E the patient. The child has a moderate fever of 38.5\u00b0C but is otherwise comfortable and stable. His vital signs are within normal limits for his age, and he is not in distress. Fever is a normal physiological response that can aid in fighting infection, and not all fevers require treatment with antipyretics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering paracetamol\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eibuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary in this case. Antipyretics are typically reserved for patients with high fever (\u003E40\u00b0C) or those who are particularly uncomfortable. This patient\u0027s fever is moderate, and he is not distressed. While antipyretics can provide comfort, they are not always required when the patient is managing well with a moderate fever. It\u0027s important to note that regular administration of antipyretics does not reduce the complications of fever including febrile seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanging antibiotic to ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this point. The patient has been on intravenous benzylpenicillin for only 12 hours, which is an appropriate first-line treatment for community-acquired pneumonia. A moderate fever alone is not a reason to change antibiotics, especially when the patient is otherwise stable and comfortable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing intravenous fluid rate\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as the patient is stable and there are no signs of dehydration or haemodynamic compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle here is that fever itself is not harmful in most cases and does not always require treatment, even in children. The focus should be on treating the underlying cause (in this case, pneumonia) and ensuring patient comfort. Regular monitoring of the patient\u0027s condition, including vital signs and overall comfort level, is important. If the fever rises significantly or the child becomes distressed, then antipyretic treatment can be reconsidered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Antipyretics are not required in all fever patients as they only treat a symptom and not a cause, but should be administered to patients with high fever (\u003E40\u00b0C) or those who are particularly uncomfortable.","Fever is a normal physiological response that can aid in fighting infection.","Careful assessment of the patient\u0027s overall condition and comfort level is crucial in deciding whether to administer antipyretics in children."],"references":["Don\u2019t routinely administer antipyretics with the sole aim of reducing body temperature in un-distressed children. In: Choosing wisely Australia 2016. Available at: https://www.choosingwisely.org.au/recommendations/acn3","Community acquired pneumonia. In: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Clinical practice guidelines 2023. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Community_acquired_pneumonia/","El-Radhi AS. Fever management: Evidence vs current practice. World J Clin Pediatr. 2012 Dec 8;1(4):29-33. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4145646/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79546"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13928"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79546"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T17:54:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-12T07:37:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6547"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96931"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/